snippet.textDisplay:
"Predictive Programming" is kind of correct, but it's the wrong way of looking at it for a lot of these. For example, some technologies and other realities unknown to the public already exist in secret, but they are revealed to "us" the "common people" via entertainment media. But these revelations are not because the powers that be know the future necessarily, but are aware of the existence of certain things... they just don't make US aware until later. They "dripfeed" us the truth.

Like the alien/UFO truth. The powers that be have been dripfeeding us that truth for decades so that we're all desensitized as more and more of the alien reality is slowly revealed.

snippet.textDisplay: It's all just an endless cycle of creativity (and advancements of technology). Innovators watch entertainment and generate ideas from them (or in the event of technology, the government/military engineers are waaaaay ahead of what is seen in the public eye). In contrast, you get entertainers seeing things that haven't happened yet and throwing in a joke about it and then when it becomes real/meta everyone thinks it was a prediction. But really, we're in a big circle that all just happens to tie in together. That being said...I'm going to predict winning the lottery, because I mean...predictions can't HURT, right?
